1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:20,000
We've talked about the advantages of symmetric key cryptography, and just to remind you, they are that...

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:37,000
that symmetric algorithms are really fast, in fact, they can encrypt to the tune of hundreds of millions of bits per second.

3
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:44,000
But the problem that symmetric has is key distribution. Now, asymmetric is the opposite, isn't it?

4
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:50,000
The advantage of asymmetric is that it gets rid of the problem of key distribution.

5
00:00:50,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Now, asymmetric is the opposite, isn't it? The advantage of asymmetric is that it gets rid of the problem of key distribution,

6
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:12,000
but introduces that slowness problem. And so that's why today all crypto systems and solutions that exist out there are actually what we call hybrid.

7
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:21,000
And hybrid simply means that they use both symmetric and asymmetric key cryptography algorithms for what they're both good at.

8
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:28,000
And so what you need to remember here is that symmetric is usually used for bulk and speed.

9
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:36,000
Anything that requires a lot of encryption, a lot of decryption, and wherever we need to do it really quickly.

10
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:46,000
Asymmetric algorithms are used to exchange these symmetric keys that are required at both ends in order to be able to do that.

11
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:56,000
So today, off cryptography solutions, implementations are what we call hybrid. And then what they'll do is they'll also add functionality to address

12
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:06,000
hashing algorithms for integrity, digital signature algorithms to address non-repediation. And that's what we call crypto system.

13
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:15,000
Really hybrid products that support all kinds of different algorithms to achieve really the five services that cryptography can for us.

14
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:21,000
But let's look at an example here of hybrid cryptography by using again Alice and Bob.

15
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:29,000
So let's say Alice wants to send a very large message to Bob because it's a very large message.

16
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:37,000
The only option that they can use is symmetric cryptography. And so let's say they've decided to use dads for this.

17
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:50,000
So what Alice does is she's going to encrypt that very large message with dads which requires her to choose one of the possible keys, symmetric keys,

18
00:02:50,000 --> 00:03:02,000
that Dez uses. Now she knows that the only way that Bob will be able to decrypt that message is to have the exact same symmetric key.

19
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:19,000
So that's the problem of key distribution that we've talked about. But Alice knows a good way to do this and send it to Bob securely because what she can do is she can take that 56-bit symmetric key that Bob requires.

20
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:39,000
And encrypt it with Bob's public key. All right, because if Alice encrypts that symmetric key with Bob's public key that ensures that the only person out there that can decrypt that is Bob with his private key that he keeps private to himself.

21
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:57,000
And so now when he receives that he will be able to decrypt it with what no one else has which is his private key at which point he will have the same symmetric key that Alice used in order to encrypt that very large message.

22
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:10,000
And Bob now will be able to decrypt very quickly as well because ultimately they both used symmetric key cryptography to be able to encrypt and decrypt that message quickly.

23
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:20,000
But they've used asymmetric key cryptography to be able to exchange the symmetric key that is required at both ends.

24
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:32,000
So this is a perfect example of what hybrid cryptography looks like today. Simply means we use a combination of symmetric and asymmetric for what they're each good at.

25
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:42,000
Symmetric always use for bulk and speed, asymmetric always use to exchange symmetric keys that are required at both ends.

